<section class="text-flow">

  <h2>What is checked during a post-storm inspection</h2>

  <p>
    Our inspection is tailored to high-end residential properties in Madeira. The focus is on visible areas that typically require particular attention after storms, rain and wind.
  </p>

  <h3>Outdoor areas and first visual assessment</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>visible roof areas and exposed surfaces</li>
    <li>façades, access points and exterior structures</li>
    <li>terraces, railings and sliding elements</li>
    <li>windows, doors and visible signs of stress</li>
    <li>loose or displaced items outdoors</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In hillside locations, coastal settings or open terrace areas, weather conditions often have a stronger impact than first assumed. An early visual inspection helps identify irregularities in time.
  </p>

</section>

<section class="text-flow">

  <h2>Gardens, furniture and outdoor structures</h2>

  <p>
    Many villas and high-end apartments include carefully maintained outdoor areas, pool zones and garden structures. After a storm, these are often the first areas affected.
  </p>

  <h3>Particularly relevant points</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>toppled or damaged plants</li>
    <li>shifted outdoor furniture and loose objects</li>
    <li>covered or exposed furniture areas</li>
    <li>pool surroundings, terrace surfaces and paths</li>
    <li>changes to walls, edges and boundaries</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The objective is not only to identify damage, but also to assess clearly which areas need immediate attention and which simply require observation.
  </p>

</section>

